---
import BaseLayout from '../../../layouts/BaseLayout.astro';
import Pagination from '../../../components/Pagination.astro';
import DocCard from '../../../components/DocCard.astro';

const base = '/portfolio';
const previous = 'huffman-compression';
const next = 'rslk';
---

<BaseLayout title="Hashes | ADEN Project" base={base}>
  <Pagination
    base={base}
    section="projects/aden"
    previous={previous}
    next={next}
  />

  <section style="max-width:900px; margin:0 auto; padding:2rem 1rem;">
    <h1>Hashes</h1>

    {/* PROJECT DESCRIPTION */}
    <section style="margin-bottom:1.5rem;">
      <h2>Project Description</h2>
      <p style="color:#444; line-height:1.6;">
        The Hashes project explores how hashing functions distribute data into fixed-size tables
        and how different collision resolution strategies affect performance. I implemented and
        tested multiple hashing techniques, comparing their efficiency under varying load factors
        and input distributions.
      </p>
      <p style="color:#444; line-height:1.6;">
        This project bridges theoretical concepts such as modular arithmetic and probability
        with practical system design decisions used in real-world data structures like hash maps.
      </p>
    </section>

    {/* VISUAL */}
    <section style="margin-bottom:1.5rem;">
    </section>

    {/* HASHING ALGORITHMS */}
    <section style="margin-bottom:1.5rem;">
      <h2>Hashing Algorithms</h2>

      <ul style="color:#444; line-height:1.7;">
        <li>
          <strong>Linear Probing:</strong> Resolves collisions by scanning sequential slots.
          Simple but suffers from primary clustering at high load factors.
        </li>

        <li>
          <strong>Quadratic Probing:</strong> Uses quadratic offsets to reduce clustering effects,
          improving distribution compared to linear probing.
        </li>

        <li>
          <strong>Linked List (Chaining):</strong> Stores multiple elements per index using linked lists,
          making performance more stable under high load factors.
        </li>

        <li>
          <strong>Cuckoo Hashing:</strong> Uses two hash functions and relocation (“kicking out” elements),
          achieving near O(1) lookup performance but with higher implementation complexity and memory use.
        </li>
      </ul>
    </section>

    {/* ANALYSIS */}
    <section style="margin-bottom:1.5rem;">
      <h2>Summary of Hash Analysis</h2>

      <p style="color:#444; line-height:1.6;">
        Across all implementations, performance varied significantly depending on load factor
        and input distribution. Surprisingly, datasets with clustered values (Dataset D)
        often performed as well as or better than uniformly distributed data due to the
        effectiveness of the hashing function in dispersing inputs.
      </p>

      <p style="color:#444; line-height:1.6;">
        Linear and quadratic probing showed expected degradation at higher load factors,
        while linked list chaining remained more stable. Cuckoo hashing consistently
        delivered the fastest lookup times, though at the cost of increased memory usage.
      </p>

      <p style="color:#444; line-height:1.6;">
        Overall, this experiment highlighted the tradeoffs between simplicity, speed,
        and memory efficiency in hash table design.
      </p>

      <div style="margin-top:1rem;">
        <DocCard
          title="Hash Analysis Report"
          pdfHref={`${base}/documents/ADEN_docs/pdf/${encodeURIComponent('Arnav Krishnan - Hash Analysis.pdf')}`}
          htmlHref={`${base}/documents/ADEN_docs/html/Arnav Krishnan - Hash Analysis/ArnavKrishnanHashAnalysis.html`}
          iframeId="hash-analysis"
          iframeTitle="Hash Analysis Report"
        />
      </div>
    </section>

    {/* KEY LEARNINGS */}
    <section style="margin-bottom:1.5rem;">
      <h2>Key Learnings</h2>

      <ul style="color:#444; line-height:1.7;">
        <li>
          Hash function design significantly impacts performance more than input distribution in many cases.
        </li>
        <li>
          Collision resolution strategies each introduce distinct tradeoffs in speed, memory, and complexity.
        </li>
        <li>
          Load factor is a critical predictor of hash table performance degradation.
        </li>
        <li>
          Empirical benchmarking often contradicts theoretical expectations and reveals real system behavior.
        </li>
        <li>
          Cuckoo hashing provides excellent performance but requires careful implementation and memory overhead.
        </li>
      </ul>
    </section>

    {/* NAVIGATION */}
    <section>
      <p>
        <a
          href={`${base}/aden-course`}
          style="color:#0055aa; text-decoration:underline;"
        >
          ← Back to ADEN Course
        </a>
      </p>
    </section>
  </section>
</BaseLayout>